###################################################################
#                       READING DOCUMENTATION                     #
###################################################################

To read the documentation for a given module ("*.pm"), simply type
'perldoc [path to module]'. Of course, you can always just open the file 
with 'vim [path to module]' (why wouldn't you be using Vim?), but that's
for those who really want to get nasty and start reading the inline comments.
The POD documentation I've provided should be enough to get you started. 

###################################################################
#                          RUNNING TESTS                          #
###################################################################

To run the tests, simply type "make test". 

If you're setup to run gobs and gobs of tests, type "make background_test". 
This will branch off a terminal w/ 'screen' and run in the background. If done
on a server, you can safely log off and allow the tests to continue running. To
see a list of the screens running, type 'screen -ls'. To connect to the screen
currently running the test, type 'screen -r scheduler_test'.
